11/26/2016

In today's presentation

  • X-road log data
  • Digital prescription: looking for signs of diffusion

What is x-road?

  • Whenever service providers, regardless of their sector, require state confirmed (or owned) information, they can get it automatically through Estonia's e-government system
  • However, e-government is not a single entity, but rather a network of different systems
  • These different systems are connected by a specific information exchange layer called the x-road

What is x-road?

  • Around 1500 services and 200 data repositories
  • Widely used

What does x-road have offer?

  • All x-road traffic is logged
    • For system maintenance and transparency reasons
  • Only four variables are logged:
    • time
    • user
    • consumer
    • service
  • Consequently, this log data can be used to analyze how different services are used
  • Over 2 billion queries from 2003 to 2015

Difficulties of using log data

  • People who build and develop IT systems are not, in fact, social scientists!
    • While this is becoming less of a problem nowadays, it will still take years to reap the rewards
  • Machine-to-machine communication is not easily distinguishable given the limited number of variables
  • Missing data from system downtime


In short: there is a lot of noise and no easy way to filter it

Digital prescription

Digital prescription

  • Service description
  • General uptake patterns
  • First and nth time users

Service description

  • Digital prescription service was developed in conjunction with a few other health related e-services (digital health records, appointment registration etc)
  • Is compulsory for pharmacies, but patients can still opt for paper-based prescriptions if they wish to do so
  • Went online in 2010

Service description

  • As with many other services, no one "digital prescription" service exists, rather a number of smaller services connected to the same object (prescription):
    • Writing prescriptions (for doctors)
    • Checking your list of prescriptions or individual prescriptions
    • Checking your patients' prescriptions (for doctors)
    • Business related services for pharmacies (are prescriptions still valid, who is eligible for discounts etc)

General uptake patterns

  • To measure that, we have to:
    • Count the number of unique prescriptions
    • Differentiate between paper-based and digital prescriptions (or know their sum)
  • Log data does not provide information about the object of the query
  • Therefore, if we want to measure unique prescriptions, we have to find a proxy indicator for it

General uptake patterns

  • Two services stand out:
    • Assigning purchase information - indicates that a purchase was made
    • Digitization service - indicates that a purchase was made using a paper-based prescription


\({Y} = \frac{1}{1 + 0.86{e}^{-2.14{\ln}(x)}}\)

General uptake patterns

  • While there are more efficient methods for modeling uptake, this demonstrates that we do get fairly accurate results with log data analysis

First and nth time users

  • In order to go further we should look how this service has diffused in different user groups and what kind of people use it more often
    • In other words: diffusion among specific user groups (age, gender, number of times used)

  • Previous services do not contain information on patients, which is why have to rely on additional sub-services

  • One of these services returns a list of prescriptions to the user (note: not patient!)
    • Gets called when users visit health related e-services or explicitly requests it from e-government's webpage
    • Around 20 000 queries every month
    • Used more by females and younger people

First and nth time users

  • To explore diffusion in different user groups, we would have create a usage counter for every unique user
  • For illustrative purposes we can continue with only the age variable

First and nth time users

  • Since the true diffusion pattern seems linear, we may apply a linear model to clean our data from machine-generated noise
